english:
  title: 'Memorial to the Ministry of Rites: A Petition to Remove Yang Xiong from the Confucian Shrine and Preserve Dong Zhongshu'
  author: Gwon Woo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To honor virtue and exalt the worthy are indeed the noble precedents of our state; to commend the good and censure the wicked are truly the steadfast principles of those who serve. With this I exhaust my humble understanding and dare to trouble your keen attention.

    Consider this: Throughout the ages, all who have contributed to the transmission of the Way have rightfully received sacrifice in the school shrine. Should true Confucian scholars be omitted, I fear the path of justice itself would suffer. When Qin brought ruin with its burning of books, our Way nearly perished. Though Han later revived the classics, genuine scholars remained scarce. Yet Dong Zhongshu grasped the great heritage of the Spring and Autumn Annals, inherited the profound legacy of Confucius and Mencius, grounded himself in human nature and destiny, and rectified the human heart—stemming the flood of profit-seeking and advancement. He elevated humanity and righteousness, clarified the nature of the Way, and restored the cosmic order that had fallen into chaos. Such a one was rare among the heroes of his age, a sage who awakened the people to truth.

    But Yang Xiong knew not the root of learning; his talent exceeded his virtue. His "Emblems of Fortune" merely flattered the usurper Wang Mang, and his muddled discourse of good and evil ultimately offended the sacred teaching. Though his "Models of Language" echoed the Analects and his "Great Mystery" imitated the symmetries of the Book of Changes, in matters of virtue and the Way he fell short—and what of his mere literary skill?

    From Tang to this present day, our examination has not been careful, and so we have rejected the worthy and taken the unworthy, losing the distinction between right and wrong. This brings no shame upon Dong Zhongshu, yet surely we should blush for Yang Xiong. I humbly pray: discern men with wisdom, and doubt not in casting out the corrupt. Clothe the pure scholar in robes of honor and grant him sacrifice after the Seventy Disciples; wield the ax against the cunning elder and make him a warning for ten thousand ages. Then shall the lesser depart and the greater arrive; rank and station find their proper place; names accord with reality and speech with truth; propriety and music flourish anew.

    I shall faithfully attend to this duty with constancy, maintaining day and night the proper order and essential principle of our sacrificial rites, never faltering, never forgetting—serving with reverence the office of the Minister of Rites.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Seventy Disciples refers to Confucius's principal students, though the traditional count is seventy-two.
  - key: ''
    value: Dong Zhongshu (董仲舒, 179-104 BCE) was a Han Dynasty Confucian scholar who developed a comprehensive political philosophy based on the Spring and Autumn Annals.
  - key: ''
    value: Yang Xiong (揚雄, 53 BCE - 18 CE) was a Han Dynasty scholar and author of the Fayan (Models of Language) and Taixuan (Great Mystery), but was criticized for his compromises with Wang Mang's regime.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Emblems of Fortune' (符命) refers to writings that supported Wang Mang's usurpation of the Han throne.
  - key: ''
    value: Gownstones (곤석) and the ax-wielders (부월) are metaphorical references to honoring the worthy and punishing the corrupt.
